{"id":"1910.09704","submitter":"Vamsi Amalladinne","authors":"Vamsi K. Amalladinne, Jean-Francois Chamberland, Krishna R. Narayanan","title":"An enhanced decoding algorithm for coded compressed sensing","comments":"Submitted to ICASSP2020","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT eess.SP math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Coded compressed sensing is an algorithmic framework tailored to sparse\nrecovery in very large dimensional spaces. This framework is originally\nenvisioned for the unsourced multiple access channel, a wireless paradigm\nattuned to machine-type communications. Coded compressed sensing uses a\ndivide-and-conquer approach to break the sparse recovery task into\nsub-components whose dimensions are amenable to conventional compressed sensing\nsolvers. The recovered fragments are then stitched together using a low\ncomplexity decoder. This article introduces an enhanced decoding algorithm for\ncoded compressed sensing where fragment recovery and the stitching process are\nexecuted in tandem, passing information between them. This novel scheme leads\nto gains in performance and a significant reduction in computational\ncomplexity. This algorithmic opportunity stems from the realization that the\nparity structure inherent to coded compressed sensing can be used to\ndynamically restrict the search space of the subsequent recovery algorithm.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Oct 2019 00:17:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-23"}
